The Republican Party's strategy against Obama's re-election
Republican leaders have justified their policies by the necessity of combating electoral fraud.
But the Brennan Center calls such a fraud a myth, with voter fraud less common in the U.S. than the number of people who die from lightning strikes.
In fact, Republican attorneys have recorded only 300 cases of voter fraud in the United States over the past decade.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on electoral participation.
In this sense, these measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
In contrast to Canada, individual states are responsible for organising federal elections in the United States.
And in this spirit, since 2009, most U.S. governments have been promulgating new laws that make it more difficult to vote or enroll in the electoral roll.
This phenomenon has seen a spike since the November 2010 election, which saw the addition of 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills restricting the right to vote were submitted in 41 states in 2011 alone.
New electoral laws require voters to present a photo ID and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws limit the period for elections in advance, disqualify the right to register on the electoral roll on the day of the election, and deprive citizens of the right to vote by registering in the criminal register.
Prior to the 2006 election, no U.S. state required a photo ID card to be presented to voters.
The first state to impose this requirement was Indiana.
The constitutionality of Indian law was confirmed by the U.S. Supreme Court in 2008.
The Republican authorities hurried to extend this procedure to other states as well.
Over the past two years, they have supported such bills in 34 states to force voters to present photo IDs.
It should be noted that unlike Quebec, U.S. citizens do not have a universal identity card, such as a health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, or 21 million people of voting age, do not own an identity card with a photo issued by their state government.
In addition, he does not have such an identity card of about five million new voters in 2012.
In addition, obtaining the required identity card often costs more than a hundred dollars.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and low-income people.
25% of African-Americans, 15% of people with incomes below $35,000; 18% of citizens over 65 and 20% of voters aged 18 to 29 therefore do not have the required photo ID.
And that's not all.
Students who are known as voters for their adherence to democratic candidates are not allowed in several states to use their identity card with a photograph exhibited by their school.
On the other hand, the same states allow members of hunting or fishing clubs who elect Republican candidates to use the cards issued by these clubs in the elections.
Until 2004, no state required a proof of citizenship in the elections.
The first such request was made by Arizona.
Since 2011, about 12 states have passed laws requiring voters to prove they are U.S. citizens.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting the number of votes cast by the Hispanic minority.
It should be noted that two out of three Spaniards prefer the democratic side.
In 2011, Republican lawmakers in eight states backed laws that abolished voter registration on election day.
They also restricted the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to voters who wish to register.
These restrictions have their consequences.
For example, during the 2004 general elections, voter registration campaigns helped to register about 10 million people.
However, the measures adopted after 2009 caused a 17% drop in the registration of new voters in 2010 compared to 2006.
Republican lawmakers then passed laws in five other states aimed at shortening the period for early elections.
For example, during the 2008 general election in Florida, African-Americans made up 33% of voters who voted in advance, although African-American voters in that state were only 13%.
It was the same with the Spanish.
They made up only 11% of all voters, but 24% of the citizens voting in advance.
On the other hand, whites, who represented 76% of all voters, made up only 46% of voters who voted in advance.
Of course, democratic legislators and their supporters strongly opposed the adoption of laws restricting the registration of voters.
Democratic governors blocked several bills by vetoing them.
In order to suspend the most controversial laws, the U.S. Attorney General even intervened.
In part, they have managed to reduce the damage.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states have passed laws requiring a photo ID.
However, the newly introduced rules will undeniably make it more difficult to exercise the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics, in particular, talk about the bias of the passed laws and consider them an obvious attempt to influence the results of the 2012 elections in key states.
The 2011 Brennan Center report shows that the states where these laws were passed represent 171 of the 270 votes in the electorate necessary to win the presidential election.
It is too early to declare with certainty that these legislative changes at the level of the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the presidential elections in 2012.
But one thing is certain today: these new provisions will have a negative impact on electoral participation.
In this sense, these measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
