However, let’s assume it’s a Higgs boson, as the risks of error seem small, and let’s look at what’s really going on.
In this world, there is an absolutely indisputable law, according to which two things cannot occur at the same time in the same place.
This rule can not be bypassed - and do not try it too hard, otherwise you will hurt yourself.
Although particle physics is a very strange world, it turns out that a similar law applies to it: Pauli's exclusion principle, according to which two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time, if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" roughly creates some of their property.
It further divides the physical particles into two categories.
On the one hand, we will find orderly citizens, or fermions, who obediently adhere to Pauli’s principle.
And at the other end there are the barons, the anarchists, who do not value anything at all - certainly not this principle, which means that they can be in the same place at the same time.
