When an electrically charged particle accelerates or changes direction, it cancels out the electromagnetic field in that particular place, like a pebble thrown into a pond.
From this "disruption" an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet rays, etc.) will arise, and this wave is nothing but a photon - and therefore one of the bosons, the "carriers of force".
A more stable field
The same is true of the Higgs boson, except that it takes a different field, the Higgs field, to "disrupt" the boson.
This Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; for its excitation it is necessary to achieve very high energy values, similar to the frozen level of the pond, which is already spread only by a very large boulder.
