In the house of Victor-Gadbois, the days go by, but they do not resemble each other.
Next to a ninety-three-year-old man, who rejoices at the last meeting with his family thoroughly laid out on the pillows, while being toasted in his honor, tragically dies a thirty-six-year-old man surrounded by his parents, a woman and two young children all over the place.
"For six months, there have been three to five beds that are intended for people with cancer under 45," says Dr. Christiane Martel.
53% of patients who come to the Victor-Gadbois home come from their homes, 47% from hospitals.
Problems with access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, i.e. care that is designed to alleviate suffering once a patient reaches the final stage of his or her life, whether at home, in a hospital, or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the Victor-Gadbois home and the Society for Home Palliative Care of the Grand Montréal area, specialize more or less exclusively in the care provided to cancer patients.
And it is precisely this fundamental unavailability of health care in Quebec that causes a number of physicians specializing in palliative care to fear the passage of the Euthanasia and Assisted Suicide Act.
Since October, the manifesto has been signed by palliative treatment leaders such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, in which they demonstrate their disagreement with such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, the Quebec health care system is not efficient enough to ensure that all people have access to quality palliative care before they can agree to euthanasia.
As she says, she recently experienced a patient who spent 14 days in an emergency room in huge pain without anyone taking the necessary steps to relieve her.
He fears that patients will not be asked to be killed because they are not receiving adequate care.
And at the same time, a number of oncologists care for their patients until the last moments, regardless of the unfavorable prognosis.
The hopes of Hél<0xC3><0xA8>ne Richard’s survival were already very low when she left demanding chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was quitting treatment, she replied that she regretted that I stopped fighting, she told us.
And yet she told me it was over!
There is no omnipotent care.
Dr. Martel estimates that 90% of patients who wish to die thank their attending physicians for not fulfilling their wishes when a team of palliative foxes relieved them of their pain.
But it must be said that palliative care is definitely not omnipotent in the treatment of pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of palliative care at the Society for Home Palliative Care of the Grand Montréal region, patients are prevented from treating pain in 8% of cases.
At the very end of life, doctors often use palliative sedatives, which sleep the patient until the moment he dies, either by shock or if the sedatives are given to him permanently.
We cannot pretend that we do not perceive this part of suffering.
A patient who is not relieved of pain will have an ever-increasing chance of access to palliative sedatives.
Patients who are not given a sedative always say the same thing: "I want to die."
But that doesn’t necessarily mean “I want you to give me euthanasia,” it means “I want you to get rid of my pain.”
