Thanks to 15,000 computers connected to the network, about 200,000 transactions have already been registered.
About a thousand websites already accept bitcoins as gifts or as a means of payment.
The bitcoin exchange rate first peaked at $30 (23 euros) in June 2011, five months later dropped to $2, today it moves to the limit of about $10 (the exchange rate overview is given on bitcoincharts.com).
Compared to the world exchange for real money or financial products, this is nothing impressive.
And yet the European Central Bank (ECB) is interested in this fact in its report on virtual finance, which came out in October.
Bitcoin refers to “the most successful virtual money,” “competitive with the dollar and the euro,” and “an era of ordinary money.”
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual money in that it is like “credits” used to progress in a video game that a person acquires through a game or can buy (and sometimes exchange back).
The social network Facebook has also developed a similar system.
Each month, however, the Central Authority monitors and processes individual communications.
In the case of Bitcoin, all network nodes are book depositors of current accounts, controllers, money issuers, and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users actually takes place between two e-mail addresses by means of an e-mail.
However, the user can choose a different address for each payment, thus ensuring anonymity.
The file of information related to this transaction is electronically signed by a double-key encryption system.
The network can verify the legitimacy of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the exchanged bitcoins exist in the public ledger of current accounts, which is distributed throughout the network.
The key phase is to write this new transaction into this book.
It takes place by solving a mathematical task assigned to computers, the solver of which, like a temporary central banker, will have the right to underwrite this additional line.
This is the cutting phase of a file; that is, the transformation of a large file into a shorter and unique digital imprint.
Computers will "take over" this new transaction and add a number to it, only then they will "cut" the whole.
The goal is to find a number that provides a specific print (a lot of zeroes at the beginning).
Once this number is found, the other nodes will easily check its correctness.
The transaction will then appear indestructibly connected to the chain of all other transactions; any modification would change the fingerprint.
If the user would like to pay twice with the same money very quickly in a row (within ten minutes), the network will confirm only one of the two transactions - the second will be abandoned, because each of them has a different fingerprint.
The computer that solves the challenge will win 50 bitcoins.
To prevent inflation, these rewards are regularly divided into two, probably by the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is so limited by the number of 21 million, but they can be divided into one hundred million, so there is room for margin here.
The difficulty of a given task also increases with the increasing level of calculation.
The network has already experienced its ups and downs.
Websites that provide services for Bitcoin have been attacked and stored bitcoins have been stolen.
"The shell used does not relate to the protocol itself," assures Pierre Noizat, who founded Paymium, a real-money payment company that uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also monitors the possibility of money laundering through this anonymous service.
But this problem also applies to cash.
Prominent players such as Wikipedia reject the gifts of this nature.
Others, like the WordPress blogging platform, accept them.
Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizmann Institute in Israel recently analyzed the ledger of current accounts and proved that almost 80% of bitcoins are not flowing.
In November, "huge discounts" were launched.
“Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged,” says Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul for the conversion of bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, who is also the author of an educational book on this money, has great confidence in the potential of this technology as a transactional network.
Its system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (with real money) or contactless mobile payment, but it uses the Bitcoin system to verify transactions that are therefore cheaper.
In addition, the wearer manages his identity and thus can remain anonymous.
The system is easy to set up for merchants where there is no need to install new terminals or software.
Just communicate the address that can be "photographed and recognized" by phone, says Pierre Noizat, who assures that it already has thousands of users.
There is a general movement to challenge hierarchical systems and transition to more horizontal systems.
“Before Bitcoin is rolled out, it will take a while, but 2013 could be decisive,” he predicts.
In addition, the ECB’s report envisages a reassessment of the various risks that are now considered to be increased if this type of money is successful.
