Difficult Work on the Egyptian Constitution
President Muhammad Mursi has made his way to the next game of poker.
While Egypt remains the most divided in its history due to the promulgation of a constitution that temporarily grants it unlimited powers, it has decided to play vabank.
On Wednesday, he announced, regardless of the opinion of everyone else, that the Constituent Assembly will approve the final text tomorrow.
Less than a week ago, the head of state granted this assembly another two months to complete the necessary work.
For almost two years, Egypt has been using a provisional text that has been supplemented many times, weakening the country’s constitutional stability and leading to legal disputes.
This new initiative further reinforced the country’s fragmentation.
From the opposition’s point of view, the president remains in his “autocratic delirium,” continues to “violate his word,” and “tramples the law.”
However, his supporters assure him that this is a means of speeding up the constitutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and speeding up the transition process.
A referendum is due to be held in two weeks.
It is a very short period of time that will force the Brotherhood to withdraw from the Egyptians’ intention to explain the text article by article.
It is also a way for the president to regain national and democratic legitimacy, while the entire country is being shaken by protests.
As confirmed in an interview with the American weekly Time, Muhammad Mursi seems to be convinced that the Egyptians will vote for it.
Particularly because this hastyly organised vote puts the Egyptian people before an ultimatum: "Either you approve my text, or I will leave you with unlimited powers" that would otherwise have to end with the approval of the new constitution.
And in this special atmosphere yesterday, 85 MPs of the aforementioned Constituent Assembly, with a large majority of Islamists, approved the text.
The majority of liberals were absent from the vote.
In mid-November, not long before the proclamation of the constitution, they knocked on the door with the fact that they had no opportunity to enforce their views.
Human rights defenders, civil society or members of religious minorities imitated their move.
In order to achieve readiness, 11 persons from the ranks of substitutes were rushed in yesterday morning.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
It is not surprising, then, that the articles of the Constitution were often voted unanimously.
Commentators further paused at the fact that one of the few disputes that day revolved around . . . hours for prayer, when some members of the committee felt that the hours in the meeting room were not set correctly.
The text, which was voted on last night, consists of 234 articles.
The subject of general attention, article 2, ultimately remains the same as the 1971 version of the Constitution and states that "the principles of Sharia law are the main source of law".
The Salafist parties, for which the introduction of Islamic law is one of the essential requirements, hoped to replace the term "principles" with the term "rules", which would allow for stricter application.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been corrected is a sign of their goodwill and respect for other parts of Egyptian society.
“Cheating,” argue liberals, who see it as a rhetorical problem.
According to them, the Islamization of the constitution takes place through other articles.
They focus in particular on Article 220, which entrusts al-Azhar university with an advisory role, in particular on issues of verification of compliance of laws with Sharia law.
According to Egypt expert Sophie Pommier, this is troubling because “people called to speak are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
You can see the beginnings of the theocracy.”
The concerns of the liberals are further heightened by the fact that the next rector of the university should be less moderate than the current one.
So far, there has been no concrete religious consequence.
With this constitution, Egypt remains a framework civil state.
Most of the lawyers who worked on this text are not Ulamites, but university workers, many of whom have studied in French schools," said Alexis Blouet, who is preparing the work on the constitutional transition in Egypt.
However, he agrees that "there may be contradictions with regard to the interpretation of Article 220, because the terms used in it belong to a religious dictionary.
In particular, there is a reference to "fiqh" [Islamic legal science, see red.].
And in the future, the question may arise to what extent civil judges are competent to express themselves."
In addition to religious pages, the text approved yesterday is heavily criticized for the extended powers it gives to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood insists that there has been a significant restriction on them compared to the former regime.
Another controversial point: the powers vested in the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the representatives of the army, the verification of the defense budget will not be carried out by the parliament, but by the National Defense Council.
In addition, the military courts will not prohibit the prosecution of civilians, as requested by the Association for the Protection of Human Rights.
These associations are talking about their doubts in the context of the text which they believe is directed against freedom.
The offence of blasphemy is maintained and insult is still prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially for the press.
In addition, no article deals with the protection of women, emphasizes Heba Morayef from the organization Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture referred to in Article 36.
This word was not mentioned in the previous constitution.
While the Egyptian president was due to deliver a televised speech last night, demonstrations are scheduled for this afternoon.
Supporters of the head of state will then demonstrate on Saturday.
In Israel are waiting for Ukrainian tourists holy places, the navel of the world and the sea of saturated salt solution
The promised land combines the greatness of biblical truths, modern comfort and the inviolability of nature.
The AaF has identified the five most important reasons why you should visit Israel.
Worshiping the Holy Places
Visit the Jordan River, where Jesus was baptized.
It is claimed that God’s mercy will descend on all who enter this “spa”.
And Galilee - the place of Jesus' miracles: turning water into wine at the wedding, walking on the water, calming the storm and filling the nets.
Here also Jesus appeared to his disciples and after the resurrection.
But the most holy places are in Jerusalem.
Believers here will walk the Way of the Pain or the Way of the Cross of Jesus (Latin Via Dolorosa).
It begins at the fortress of Antonia - Pretoria - where the trial took place, passes through the streets of the Old City and leads to the Temple of God's tomb on Mount Golgotha - to the place of the crucifixion, the stone of the anointing and the place where Jesus was buried.
Here is the symbolic Christian navel of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of mankind.
And the Monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem was built on the site where, according to the Christian legend, the tree grew from which the cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus.
In Jerusalem there is also the most sacred place for Jews - the Wall of Crying, the rest of the temple, which was destroyed by the Romans in 70 AD.
According to tradition, people of different faiths leave notes with wishes, which are then fulfilled.
Entering the path vertically
The ruins of the fortress of Masada remained a secret hiding place from the enemy, which Herod the Great built in 25 BC for his family.
The ruin is located on the cliffs in the mountains at an altitude of 450 m above sea level.
Only those who are involved in climbing can reach it with their own strength.
The rest will be taken to this historic mountain by cable car.
And in the north of the country, at an altitude of 1600-2040 m, there is the famous Hermon ski resort, which experiences a huge influx of tourists in the winter months.
To this ski paradise, tourists are transported by a shuttle bus from the foot of the hill.
The total length of the mountain slopes is 45 km.
According to ancient legend, pagan gods lived on the top of the mountain.
Visit the unique museums
There are about 300 museums in the country.
You can’t visit all of them in one trip.
But at least five of them, the most interesting, are definitely worth a visit.
Among them is the Museum of Israel, which is located near the Knesset (parliament).
It contains ancient manuscripts, or scrolls from the Dead Sea, found in the caves of the Judean Desert, and approximately 500,000 archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
Also worth a visit is the Tel Aviv Museum of Art.
In his exhibition, the Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall, Picasso are widely represented.
In Akkon, you can visit the Al Basha Spa Museum, which presents to visitors several rooms of ancient Turkish spas with figures of the users of the spa and spa nurses of the time.
In Caesarea, it is worth visiting the unique private Ralli Museum, where you can admire the statues of Dal<0xC3><0xAD> and Roden.
There are no guides or souvenir shops in the area.
Entrance is free and gifts are strictly refused.
The Fifth Museum - the Yad Vashem Museum in Tel Aviv - tells the story of one of the most dramatic sites in history.
The most tragic part of the museum - the Children's Memorial - was built in memory of 1.5 million children who were murdered in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You go inside – and you find yourself in complete darkness.
The stars are shining.
And there are the names of the Jewish children and the names of the countries in which they died.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
Improving Your Health
Israel’s three major spa resorts lie on the shores of the Mediterranean, Red and Dead Seas.
Each of them offers swimming pools, aqua parks, dolphinariums and oceanariums.
Interestingly, you can swim in the Red Sea even in the winter months, because the water temperature in it does not fall below 21 degrees Celsius and the air warms up to 23 degrees.
The Dead Sea is even warmer, and people bathe in it all year round.
By the way, the Dead Sea is the strangest sea in the world, located at the lowest point on the planet - at a level of 417 m below sea level.
The azure water in it is a saturated saline solution that easily keeps on the surface even people who are unable to swim.
The surrounding landscape is unrealistically beautiful.
Go here to undergo treatment with salt water - brine, and healing mud that can treat health problems with dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes, to cure your broken nerves.
Touch the Mysterious of the Ancient Past
It is protected by the ancient part of Tel Aviv - the small town of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
They were crossed by a famous sea route connecting Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
Mentions of this city are found in the oldest Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, this is the place where Noah built his ark and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with whom they then lived a long and happy life together.
Tourists really love hiking along the narrow alleys named after the signs of the zodiac.
It is said that if you press against the walls in the alley of "your" sign, happiness will be favorably inclined to you.
In Jaffa, you may meet newlyweds who come here from all over Israel and even from other countries to be photographed.
And in Caesarea - in the city of King Herod - you can walk through the Roman theater and "conquer" the fortress of the Crusaders.
In Roman times, Caesarea was the capital of Judea and the seat of Roman prosecutors, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully reconstructed theatre is now used for evening concerts and opera performances.
Tourists, in a word
If you are going to Israel, you do not have to worry about your imperfect English: in this country about 30% of the population speaks Russian.
On the way, it is better to take money with you not in euros, but in dollars, which you can easily exchange for cheques (now 1 dollar is about 3.8 shekels).
Buses are mainly used by the city, but in Jerusalem there is a high-speed tram and in the city of Haifa the only metro line in the country with six stations that connects the lower city with the upper one.
Basically, it's an underground cable car.
Travelling by all types of public transport costs 6 shekels, for which you can drive 1.5 hours with a transfer.
According to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is celebrated on the Sabbath in Israel.
From Friday evening until sunset on Saturday, he stops working in markets, shops and public transport.
On Sunday morning, the work week begins.
In many cafes, restaurants and hotels you get only kosher food: except pork, seafood, fish without scales and dishes that contain a combination of milk and meat.
They offer a large selection of dishes from lamb and beef, soups and desserts, prepared from coconut milk, traditional Jewish porridge hummus, various types of sauces, balls of ground porridge - falafel, fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs on the streets of Israeli cities.
