In recent days, there has been a wave of protests in America against low wages in Walmart hypermarkets and restaurants of popular fast food chains, such as "McDonald", "Burger King", "Taco Bell", "Wendy's" and "Kentucky Fried Chicken".
So far, no one can predict whether this wave will turn into wave nine, or whether it is destined to soon disappear.
All this action is supported by trade unions and a number of left-wing social organizations.
In addition to increasing the modest salaries that line workers receive at Walmart and in fast food systems, the goal of the protest organizers is to achieve creation in their trade unions.
At present, this economic sector is virtually unaffected by the trade union movement.
46 cents a year?
The events began last week after Thanksgiving, on the so-called "Black Friday", when an orgy of cheap sales hit America, captivated millions of residents and in some cases was accompanied by fights.
On this day, some employees of Walmart, which employs 2.2 million people worldwide, left their workplaces and demonstrated together with trade unions and left-wing activists of transnational chain companies whose goods are intended for people from the lower and middle classes.
Walmart sells everything from diapers to hunting rifles and car batteries to vacuum cleaners, eggs and milk.
Products in its stores are on average 8% to 27% cheaper than in large supermarkets.
That’s why many low-wage employees at Walmart stores only shop at work.
The availability and assortment of goods have made Walmart one of the largest companies in America.
According to critics, Walmart can afford to sell goods so cheaply in part because it pays its employees little.
They also complain of poor working conditions, such as a lack of automatic trolleys or manual scanners.
Demonstrators on “Black Friday” demanded an increase in wages and complained that the company’s health insurance costs rose sharply from $30 to $100 a month.
A typical Walmart employee gets $9.5 an hour, but that doesn’t match the level of spending, employees say.
Scientists from the University of California at Berkeley prove that if Walmart raises its average salary to $12 an hour, it will cost the company $3.2 billion a year.
This is on average 1.1% more than this company spends on wages now.
If Walmart shifts wage increases fully on the shoulders of consumers, each visit to the store will cost only 46 cents more.
In a year, customers will spend about $12.39 more than they do today.
Walmart advocates point out that the protest took place in only nine countries and the company should not cause virtually any harm.
"Black Friday" in the company's stores lasted from 8 p.m. on Thursday to midnight the following day, and during this time Walmart sold about 5,000 items of merchandise per second.
In total, its treasuries made nearly 100 million transactions on “Black Friday.”
In an interview with the left-wing website Huffington Post, Dan Fogelman said that fewer than five Walmart employees had left their jobs and that the protest was "another media sensation" organized by the unions.
"The unoccupied treasury!"
The protests continued this week in New York City, where they were not targeted by Walmart's commercial houses (those in the aforementioned progressive city are not very popular, and therefore almost not here), but by "McDonald" and other cheap restaurants.
McDonald says he sells billions of servings, and then he doesn't even pay you sick and he doesn't pay you properly for your honest work!
Jumaane Williams, New York City Councillor
Currently, the minimum wage for work in accordance with federal laws and New York State regulations is $7.25 per hour.
Fast-food restaurants are gradually increasing this wage, but only slightly, and on average, their line workers in New York receive $8.90 per hour.
No one in this expensive city has a lower salary.
I don't understand how you can live in New York for that kind of money.
Nearly a quarter of American teenagers who work part-time after-school work and live with their parents will be employed at McDonald’s.
Few people see their main source of livelihood in it or plan to stay there for too long.
Currently, I’m constantly meeting in an interview with McDonald’s workers who complain that they have to live off this money and sometimes even feed their children.
On the other hand, there is a comment on the Wall Street Journal forum, the author of which notes that it is irresponsible to have children if you do not know how to feed them.
The protests, which began at 6:30 a.m. Thursday at McDonald’s on 40th Street and Madison Avenue, demanded that cashiers and chefs at fast-food businesses start to receive at least $15 an hour, more than double their current minimum wage.
They also demanded that trade unions be established in the area of fast food.
U.S. law prohibits the administration from preventing the establishment of trade unions and from punishing trade union activists by harassment and dismissal.
On the other hand, management rarely makes life easier for them.
However, it is also difficult for objective reasons to set up a trade union in fast food establishments.
One of the main reasons is the unusually high fluctuations of employees.
Disagreement
On this day, loud protests also took place in a number of other cheap restaurants in Manhattan.
The culmination of the event was a noon meeting at McDonald's near Times Square, where several local Democratic politicians spoke, notably City Council member Jumaane Williams, who said, "McDonald says he's selling billions of servings, and then he's not even paying you your sick pay and not paying you properly!"
Demonstrators also received the support of other prominent New York Democrats, such as Mayor Bill de Blasio, who said that "we must stand up together to support fast food workers so that they achieve the fair rewards for their work and the economic prosperity that every newory deserves!"
As the New York Times described it, it was the largest event of its kind in the history of the American fast food industry.
But it was attended by only a few hundred people, although not all of them were fast-food workers, who employ tens of thousands of people in New York.
Whether this event will become a spark that will ignite the flame of the mass movement is still unclear.
