Among fans of modern virtual reality technologies is a popular theme of augmented reality; lately it means perceiving the world especially through the fringe of special glasses.
In early summer, at its annual conference, Google presented a working model of the novelty, and in November it was announced that Microsoft had also filed a patent application for the novelty.
An interview with the head of the group of interactive 3D technologies in the Cambridge laboratory of Microsoft Sharam Izadim shows that for the scientists of this company, glasses are already a thing of the past.
The perspective is the manipulation of virtual objects in the air with bare hands, the creation of virtual public spaces.
- Please tell us the framework, what does your research group deal with?
- We deal with human interactions with machines, but at the same time we try to push the boundaries of this interaction.
Humanity has so far been stuck in the stage of working with pixels on a flat screen, at most touching the screen with a finger.
We want to look 5-10 years ahead and anticipate significant changes in this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and Kinect sensors - this is a step forward, and almost no Xbox today is not for sale without Kinect sensors, because for everyone is a very interesting option to control using gestures.
- What else awaits us in the future?
Despite the fact that the Kinect system has taken interaction to the physical level, a lot of interactions are still taking place on a flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
The input flow of information has improved (the system receives more data), but the output flow has not yet been separately.
We are trying to change that, we are working on really three-dimensional imaging systems based on different technologies, including projective ones.
It is necessary to let the computer world into our physical world, to make it more real.
For this purpose, however, it is necessary to know not only the user, but also the space around him.
Then we will be able to add virtual objects in a much more suitable form to the real world.
And first of all - to hell with those stupid virtual reality helmets!
- What do you think about voice control?
That's a popular thing, but isn't it overrated?
- It can certainly not be considered a medicine - the question of privacy arises, because we do not always want to inform others around us about our activities and intentions.
In fact, all types of interactions with computers are good, but in their own environment.
For example, to control devices in public places, we had a project in which we thought about gestures, but not about bulky ones, just about such sloppy ones, short ones.
The gesture would not be perceived by a camera device, but by a bracelet that would monitor the movements of bones and muscles.
So far it is large, but theoretically it can be reduced to the size of a wristwatch.
In general, however, the future has a mixed type of control, such as gesture + voice.
- How's that?
- For example, how would you ask me to give you this can of lemonade?
You will say it and show it at the same time.
- I usually just talk.
- Oh, it'll be very difficult to recognize.
- So you want to make users adapt to what the machine can or can't do at the moment?
- It's not necessary at all, but it's a rapprochement.
I think that in the near future we will have to work primarily on the development of new types of sensors that can more accurately detect human reactions.
These can be, for example, laser sensors that provide a fairly good depth resolution, this is very important.
- If you have to talk about your work with Xbox Kinect sensors, what are your requirements for modern cameras?
Isn't there enough resolution, depth, or something else today?
- Basically the current generation - that's what we can reflect on in our work on three-dimensional recognition.
Of course, it would be good to get 8 megapixels at a speed of 1000 f/s.
But it's not just about the megapixels themselves, but as a matrix and depth.
With the current view of the matter, all current technologies are insufficient for us - this assigns work to the designers of algorithms.
So we need to keep in mind not only the resolution in the X and Y axes, but also the Z.
So it is also very important the speed, the number of frames per second.
Human movement is quite dynamic and the current data flows of 30 frames per second are frankly a little bit, especially for gestures.
Stephen Betishes from our Redmond lab made a touch sensor with an adjustable processing delay of 1 to 100 ms, while the current, mass-produced sensors are closer to the second value (60-100 ms).
Not everyone understands the extent to which it affects a person’s interaction with a machine.
For me at work would be a very useful equivalent of such a device, not only do I not need so many touches, but I need some extra shots per second.
- And there's no need to increase the number of cameras?
- The Kinect system now uses three "cameras", one of which is actually an infrared transmitter and the other - a receiver of the reflected signal.
And the third camera - it's actually a common sensor of visible band.
This is not used to determine the depth of the object.
A larger number of cameras could potentially solve the problem...
Or make it worse, because it would increase the necessary volume of calculations carried out.
It would be nice to create a flexible analogue Kinect system, play with curving the position of the cameras and see how it will help in determining the three-dimensional position.
As far as I can remember, Microsoft (unlike Google) did not publicly present its glasses.
Don’t you think that when it comes to everyday use of augmented reality technology with special glasses, it’s one of the most promising platforms?
- Of course, walking and constantly holding the smartphone in your raised hands is not very comfortable, but I think: the strongest option would be the "portable" version of the extension of reality, where it would be possible to switch from glasses to a smartphone, a projection display and so on.
Glasses - this is a very personal device, it is their strength (private things only you see), and at the same time also weakness - augmented reality based on glasses will not allow you to work on virtual objects simultaneously with other people.
- Imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holographic objects in the air is available not only to Tony Stark in "Iron Man", but also to the ordinary mortal.
There is one problem critics often point to: there is no touch response!
Hands don't feel anything!
What are the responses your group is preparing for this challenge?
In my lectures, I often say that augmented reality is the seventh consecutive breakthrough in the interaction between man and machine.
I think the addition of tactile sensations could easily become the eighth breakthrough.
So far, one of the interesting tricks is used - the use of the second hand as a certain type of substrate for display.
It records the compression in an excellent way!
But there are also technologies that are really focused on adding tangibleness to these “pictures in the air” — for example, interference by several directional ultrasound rays at a defined point where the finger is located — evokes a tactile sensation, but it’s still very weak — as if you were blowing on your fingertips.
There is also a wrist bracelet that affects the nerve endings in the fingers - also a promising direction.
Have you tried to fool the brain yet?
To think that he feels what he seems to feel at the moment when he sees something?
- That's a good idea, we haven't tried it yet.
Here is another challenge that will be fought for a long time to come - how to get a person who is physically in a very tight space to believe that he is walking in an open, practically infinite space - we are also working on the concept of running tracks (not at all such as in clubs), moving platforms and also
If brain deception becomes a goal, then work is still for many years.
That's what makes virtual reality work so attractive to researchers - many things are in their prime.
