In an interview for Aktu<0xC3><0xA1>ln<0xC4><0x9B>.cz, Vice President of the Supreme Audit Office Miloslav Kala says this.
"The law will never be perfect, but it must be applied correctly - that's what I think is missing," Kala said.
Similar conclusions are also suggested by the joint control of the Czech and German inspectors.
As an example of incorrect practice, Peter Ne<0xC4><0x8D>as' approach to the so-called "black system" is cited.
Recently the Prime Minister said that the ODS will not bother the entrepreneur with his checks - is it forbidden or allowed?
"The law must be set up somehow, and if it prohibits something, then even the Prime Minister cannot prevent an office that has the duty to control and enforce obligations," Kala said.
At the meeting of the control committee in the Chamber of Deputies, you spoke about a joint project between the Czech and German parties, in which the legislation on public procurement in both countries was compared.
What exactly was it?
It's a parallel check we started about two years ago.
To put it simply, European legislation regulates the way in which public procurement is handled, followed by individual national legislations and then by practice itself.
We have put all this together, and even though the checks have not yet been completed, we have seen very interesting differences - in general, the legislation is perhaps "stricter and more perfect" in our country, but the practice itself is better in some parameters in Germany.
It is therefore confirmed that it is not enough to create more and more precise rules, but it is necessary to devote ourselves to the application of the law itself.
What can this project do for you, what can it do for you?
It is this kind of joint control that could help us to stop trying to make laws more precise, to reduce and to improve limits, if it does not have such a positive impact.
Economics means getting the right thing at a reasonable (but not always the lowest) price to avoid enrichment and possibly criminal acts.
But by lowering the order limit, we don’t necessarily have to do that.
Perhaps the system is loaded with so much "paper" that those who want to look for holes in the system will draw from it much easier than if the limit remained higher.
You are talking about domestic problems with the transposition of public procurement legislation into practice.
How does the control system work in Germany?
Is there a similar system to ours, or is it set differently?
As far as the authorities are concerned, the Bundesrechnungshof, which is organised in the same way as we are, also has a college, is only formed in a slightly different way, but in principle both authorities proceed in a similar way.
The powers are also to some extent similar, but because Germany has a federal arrangement, it also has these accounting courts at the level of individual federal states - this is a little different from our system.
BRH can only control federal money, represented by state funds.
Public funds, which are managed by the county and municipalities, are controlled there from the level of federal accounting courts.
As for the legislation there, is it easier than ours?
In general, I would not like to compare this without specific data, but in some respects Germany is sometimes referred to as a model, but it can certainly not be said that it is better in everything.
Is it possible to have better controllers?
No, but again, I don't like comparisons like that.
But it must be said that even countries that we consider to be a model face a number of problems.
Otherwise, it wouldn't be of any use to them to cooperate with our office, would it?
As for the domestic legislation, which for your office meant the amendment of the Public Procurement Act, are its effects already manifest?
Since the validity of this amendment is relatively short, it is not yet manifested in our control actions.
Since we are doing ex post checks, we need to expect a certain delay.
We are only seeing this in the process of preparing for future checks - we have launched our new tool "risk detection of inefficiency", through which we have driven almost 14,000 public contracts, and we have analysed them - there the changes will of course manifest themselves as the limits change, the conditions of some types of tenders are adjusted and the form.
So do you consider the passage of this law to be a benefit or a further burden on the bureaucracy system?
I think this law is certainly a step in the right direction, and I hope it will be confirmed.
The problem that can happen here is that she "strengthens" the rules and will not be able to comply with them.
Already during the operation of the previous rules, the controlled persons are obliged by the provider (for example, in the case of regional operational programmes by the regional council) to assume that any non-compliance with the Public Procurement Act constitutes a violation of the budgetary discipline.
Does the law need to be tightened in this way?
I don't think so.
The system must exclude those who want to attack and abuse it, and not punish those who commit a formal error that has no impact on decision making.
Such a system will only create more pressure on the bureaucracy.
So how do we get out of this?
Let's show ourselves where the road doesn't lead.
Recently, the Prime Minister said that the ODS would not bother the entrepreneurs with the controls of the so-called "black system" - and what does that mean?
Is the black system banned or allowed?
After all, the law must be set up in some way, and if it prohibits something, then even the Prime Minister cannot prevent the activity of an authority that has the duty to control and enforce obligations.
He can say, "We'll change the law and allow it," but he can't say that we're going to act like nothing.
In the Public Procurement Act, there are fairly strict rules as to what is to be done formally - which is right to protect public competition.
But on the other hand, it is tragic when the interested party with the best offer is excluded only for formal shortcomings.
The law will never be perfect, but it must be applied correctly – that is what I think is missing.
