Poland and space.
Last week, at the meeting of the ministers of the countries of the European Space Agency, Poland was accepted as the twentieth member of the European Space Agency, as the second country from the countries of the former Eastern Bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of ESA on 12 November 2008).
Poland began close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and participated in a number of ESA projects over the following years.
However, Poland’s journey into space began much earlier.
Polish enthusiasts spent years in space before World War II; but they did not always meet with understanding.
I will recall, for example, the lecture by A. Sternfeld at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory, which on 6 December 1933 presented ideas from his pioneering work Introduction to Cosmonautics.
The ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the listeners cold and after years <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld won the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Prize for Entrance to Cosmonautics in France.
The aforementioned Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a great promoter of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He has published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and has written a number of books devoted to these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski became a world-renowned promoter of cosmonauts and his contribution was also appreciated by the fact that one of the craters on the reverse side of the Moon was named after him.
Already in 1925, a railway dresina was built in Poland, which was to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of the proposal is not known and the details of the project are not known.
It is not even clear whether the rocket should have been used to launch the drezin or to brake it.
Information about this dressage is known only from the periodical press.
From 1933, the Polish artillery began to take up missiles.
The research was carried out by the Armament Technology Cell in cooperation with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfek and Prof. Gustav Mokrzyckieg.
From the preserved materials it is clear that the research has reached the stage of practical tests.
However, with the arrival of the German troops, the research was interrupted.
In 1937, the design of a photoelectric fighter rocket, designed by Rohozi<0xC5><0x84>ski, appeared in the professional press, and in the following year the work of Rakieta - the air torpedo and the rocket bomb by Leliwy-Krzywoblocky was published.
Both projects were intended for military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy) was devoted to all projects of military use of missile technology, which coordinated all the work.
The Committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of activity it ended the beginning of the war.
Other works devoted to cosmonauts appear in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Astronautical Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time there is a mention of the company in the November issue of the 1954 issue of the journal Problems, in which there are four more extensive articles devoted to astronautics.
In one of them, from Prof. M. Subotowicze, it is proposed to create a society that will deal with cosmonauts.
At that time, projects of artificial satellites were already underway and it was clear that space research is a prospective field.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) has been trying to join the International Astronautical Federation (founded in 1951) and already in the fall PTA became a regular member.
And in the following year, the first president of PTA Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959) became vice-president of the International Astronautical Federation.
He held this position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, PTA has been a major contributor to the development of the very successful meteorological rocket RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first RM-1 was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
The rocket with access of 1800 meters was about 80 cm long and its weight was less than 5 kg.
An improved version of the RM-1A was later built, and in the summer of 1959 a flight test of the two-stage RM-2 rocket was launched in the Bled desert.
The rocket was 1.4 meters long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another type of development was already capable of real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket was supposed to have access to 14.5 km and its task was to monitor the high-altitude wind.
However, further development was suspended in 1962.
The successor of the first RM-type missiles became the Meteor-1 missile developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was conceived as a two-stage, its total length was 510 cm and the launch weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types (labelled Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed, which differed in the size of space for scientific instruments.
In the Meteor-1A rocket was available space with a volume of 0.4 liters, Meteor-1B with a volume of 0.34 liters and Meteor-1C with a volume of 0.62 liters.
The maximum access for all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Air Institute, the first flight tests of which began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had a launch weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a payload of 10 kg to a height of about 60 km.
Later versions of Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 were built.
It is necessary to mention the entry of Poland into the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the creation of the National COSPAR Committee two years later.
Poland was also involved in space research on Soviet artificial satellites as part of the Intercosmos program, and in 1978 Polish pilot Miroslav Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remko.
Repealing the Public Works Act is not the solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court overturned the Public Works Act.
The resolution sparked a lively debate in public.
It will certainly be interesting to look at this issue from a broader perspective.
Liberally oriented economic systems in the EU as well as in the globalised world are based on the principle of more, unregulated competition.
In effect, this means that individual economic units, national economic systems, are in permanent conflict with each other.
The cause is the principle of free trade and free, unrestricted movement of private capital along with unrestrained financial speculation.
Due to the significant differences in the price of labour, (wage) there is a price tension.
By this term, it is necessary to mean the state in which a producer tries to maintain competition by importing cheap goods by "subjugating" a competitor's price in order to draw on itself a greater market share and thereby increase its own profits.
On a mass scale, this means for most entrepreneurs either to move production abroad, or there to buy cheaply, or to disappear.The result is high unemployment in countries where labour prices are high compared to other economies.
Since private capital has no social responsibility and thus no responsibility for the unemployment produced by it, the social expenditures of the state necessarily increase.
The whole situation is compounded by the complete reluctance of businessmen to pay taxes and thereby compensate for the economic and social damage he has caused in the pursuit of profit.
The situation is so well known that it is not necessary to provide specific statistics.
The ruthless practices of private capital create in individual economies a situation in which the governments of individual countries are forced to enter into mutual competition in order to artificially reduce the social level of their own population in order to attract foreign capital to the country.
In other words, governments give private capital to its own population, regardless of social decline.
This is mainly reflected in changes to the applicable laws.
The aim is to economically force the own population to accept the price dictates of private capital, especially in the area of wages.
This is done both by the system of economic coercion in the case of long-term unemployment and by the restriction of the rights of employees in the field of labour law.
The result is rising poverty, along with an increase in disparities between the poor and the rich.
There have been public food outlets in the SRN for many years for the poor who cannot live on their own labour.
The number of these people is already in the millions.
In the context of increasing the competitiveness of the German economy, it is quite common for properly employed people to receive such wages that they have to be paid to the existential minimum.
Such a scandal was also published in the case of auxiliary employees of the Federal House.
The austerity measures of virtually all the southern EU states undoubtedly lead to the same situation when people are forced to emigrate under the pressure of a catastrophic collapse of the social level, either as it was in the 19th century, or to live on starving wages on the fringes of society in the hope that someday private investment capital will come to the country.
But here we have to ask where it comes from.
If it comes from other EU countries, then poverty is moving from one country to another, or it will not come at all, because the Chinese, the Indian, the Brazilian, or the Turkish, the Moroccan, or the Egyptian, or the African are still working for a fraction of the European wage.
This applies to the whole of Latin America.
Liberal theories and the media argue that the state cannot participate in its own economy by capital, that a controlled economy leads to an economic disaster.
Private capital insists strongly on the position that the state must not interfere with the economy through management interventions.
Then it is necessary to ask whether private capital does not influence, now it actually governs politics and thus the whole state in its own egoistic sense.
Here is a clear answer yes.
The evidence is the existence of a virtually omnipotent and ubiquitous lobby in all states.
The result is a desperate situation manifested in the area of corruption, the provision of mutual benefits, legislation, where practically everything is punishable, but nothing is criminal.
In the SRN, the situation is such that, due to lack of funds, the ministries of state order the drafting of laws to private law firms, which are rigid in connection with industry.
These bills are then approved by the Bundestag.
All power in this way does not come from the people, as Western-type constitutions say, but from financially strong groups that prefer self-interest.
It is clear that liberally oriented democracies are now rapidly getting into a situation, as Appianus describes it in his Crisis of the Roman Republic during the times of Caesar and Pompeii: "The state has long been in complete disarray and the authorities have been occupying themselves with violence.
For bribes, illegal gain of favor, and the use of stones or swords.
Corruption and bribery roared without any hindrance, and the people went to the elections with a pre-sold vote, but the people did not apply for office at all, so once, as a result of this upheaval, it was possible to stand for eight months without consuls. . . .
Conclusion As in antiquity, today’s society is based on a ruthless preference for self-interest, regardless of the interest of society as a whole.
Private capital is by its very nature no longer able to understand and apply the benefits of society as a whole.
The result is now, as at the time, an unprecedented decadence of elites without any effort to reform more deeply.
We must therefore seek the causality of the rise of fascist and communist regimes in the ruthless liberalization of the economic systems of the 19th and 20th centuries.
In the current state of affairs, the demise of these systems in favour of a liberal type of democracy can be regarded as a certain pause in anticipation of the next round.
Particularly disastrous is the fact that current elites are completely ignoring the possible hundreds of thousands of lives lost in the future, humanitarian and social disasters that we are already witnessing together with crimes against humanity, as we know from old and new history.
The repeal of the Public Works Act is not a solution, at least not a permanent one.
