The difficulty is that it has been defined and discussed in many different ways, said John D. Eastwood, a professor of psychology at York University in Ontario, Canada.
After looking at the research literature and presenting the idea to a target group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues defined boredom as an experience “I wanted to do something that would satisfy me, but I was not able to do it”.
Boredom is different from apathy in that a person is not involved in anything, but would like to be.
