It is the company PT Candi Ngrimbi, which has been mining in the volcano since 1960 and has never paid its employees more than 662 Indonesian rupees (five cents) per kilogram of sulphur.
Then it sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 cents) to the petrochemical industry, as this mineral has its place in everyday life and is used for the manufacture of matches, fun pyrotechnics, cosmetics, dynamite and even for sugar bleaching.
"Because we normally carry 70 kilos, we earn about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) for each trip," explains Anto, who usually does three trips a day.
One trip takes him three hours and in the end he is destroyed, but he can earn 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) per day.
Although it seems like a negligible amount for such inhumane efforts, it is three times what he would have earned in the field.
"The daily wage of miners is very high here. For example, for collecting coffee, 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) are paid per day and the salary in fourteen days is two million rupees (167 euros)," explains the carrier, who previously worked on the tourist island of Bali as a bricklayer.
There was his salary of 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day and work was not so difficult, but Anto returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a village near the volcano, for a serious reason that is as convincing in Indonesia as sulfur: "I married a young girl from Bali, who is a Jav is a Hindu, and she is a J<0xC4><0x81>l<0xC4><0x81>va."
Anto has asthma, he's breathing badly, he's still coughing and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases
At the age of 27, Anto risks life in the Kawah Ijen volcano three times a day, whose sulphur has already begun to collect its tax on him, even though his face is protected by a special mask and glasses.
He has asthma, he's breathing badly, he's still coughing, and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases that escape from the volcano.
This is the price he has to pay to achieve his dream.
“I’m going to work for another two years because I want to open a store or study Spanish or French,” he says.
This sympathetic and intelligent young man arrived by fate could be a tourist guide, waiter or receptionist at the hotel, and instead does the work of a carrier.
It shares a dirty wooden hut with other carriers and wakes up every day at two o'clock in the morning, because the sulphur does not cease to ooze at night and its characteristic yellow color turns to blue and shines dark.
Despite the surrounding darkness, Anto wanders into the crater and lights his way with a small torch, which he has attached to his helmet and bought for his own money.
About 400 carriers carrying sulfur from the bottom of the crater on the shoulder basket
Although the company has high revenues, due to cost savings, it has not mechanized sulphur mining, nor does it provide carriers working on their own and with such an effort, with any equipment.
In fact, they don’t even get a share of 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) from the photography surcharge, which, along with a ticket for 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros), is picked up by the nature park’s guardians from tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its human mules.
“This job is for cattle, not people,” says Madrusin, a 42-year-old sturdy carrier who has been working in Kawah Ijen for three decades since he left school.
She manages to lift up to 110 kilos and assures us that she will last to work “as long as possible” because she needs the money to educate her three sons between the ages of 18 and 10.
I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano has been my whole life
Although the sulphur burns the throat and gnaws in the eyes, when the wind unexpectedly turns and catches the miners in dense vapors coming out of the volcano, the miners are so stubborn that none of them complain that they suffer from serious diseases... but it is clear that they suffer from arrhythmias and arrhythmias of their frequent respiratory sweats.
Unainik, who balances his basket on his back, can only carry 50 kilograms at the age of 53.
Every day, he and his colleagues dump 15 tons of sulphur into the volcano, which is then transported by three trucks along a steep road between the pontoon and the warehouse in Tamansari, 18 kilometers away.
"I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano has been my whole life," Unainik says, opening his mouth wide, missing a few teeth.
Of his five sons, the eldest, a thirty-year-old, also earns by mining sulfur.
Time passes, but the constant misery of one of the world's most difficult crafts persists from generation to generation - the crafts performed by human mules in Kawah Ilyn.
