What is private offline is private and online
-Privacy.
According to a dictionary published by the Royal Spanish Academy, it is something of a personal nature or “an area of private life that everyone has the right to protect against any interference”.
What is privacy for a person under the age of 16?
How does he apply this definition in his daily life and on social networks?
Does he understand the dangers he faces when he publishes things on the Internet that he would certainly not tell anyone in normal communication?
Journalists from elPeri<0xC3><0xB3>dico interviewed five boys and girls between the ages of 10 and 15, who are frequent users of the Internet.
In four cases, they considered the concept of privacy to be "something entirely personal" on the personal level and to be a "username and password" when it came to social networks.
“I wouldn’t disclose my biggest secret,” says 10-year-old Jorge, trying to explain the importance of privacy in places like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he has had accounts for two years.
"They're very secret secrets, my mom can know about them, but not the whole world," he says.
"I'm posting nice pictures or pictures of us playing on FB.
I also talk to people I know.
I wouldn’t share a photo that wasn’t mine, or a photo that would make someone laugh,” he says.
This boy realizes that it is wrong to publish obscene photos, photos of naked people or photos of crimes, or to write humiliating or rude comments.
Jorge says he knows all 35 friends he has on FB and his nine followers on Twitter.
Most of them are relatives.
Among them is a mother who has the name and password of one of the accounts.
“I created a Twitter account so that I could express my views and write interesting posts.
I don’t know if anyone will answer me, I just put them there,” he adds.
“Social networks are fun, I can talk to relatives who are far away or communicate quickly with friends,” she says.
Without hesitation, he says he would never accept a request from an unknown person.
He wouldn't even care if someone recommended him to someone he didn't know.
The case of 14-year-old Joseph is different.
This teenager owns accounts on the networks Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask and on the last mentioned network admits that he does not know 20 people from his list of friends.
“I’m not afraid of it because we have something in common, like music,” he says.
According to this boy, none of them were pointing him at anything, nor did they want an address or a phone number after him.
“If they insist on me or ask me to do so, I will simply remove them from my account,” he admits.
José signed up for Ask after reading the recommendations on Twitter.
These boys are not strangers to the experience of what is now called cyberbullying.
"A well-known friend was blackmailed on social media.
They threatened him and demanded money.
He never knew who it was," he said.
According to Jose, the victim did not log out of the account.
"You've just activated your private mode."
It then explains a series of steps on how to securely set up an account.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would post photos of acquaintances in awkward or embarrassing situations.
"Of course I would do it if someone bothered me or just wanted to.
Even though I know it's cyberbullying," he says.
Key Issues
Marielos Porras, a teacher of English and a graduate of the field of Education and Teaching, believes that in order for children and adolescents to be properly oriented in social networks, they must understand that the main goal of these networks is to inform them.
"The Internet was created as a means of searching for information, but when social networks appeared, the rules of the game changed."
Marrielos Porras notes that academician Marc Prensky, a graduate of pedagogy at Yale University and author of the article Digital Natives and Digital Immigrants, introduced these concepts to explain this phenomenon.
“Digital natives are children and young people who were born at the time of this technology.
We are digital immigrants who need to be taught, and yet we are still learning by ourselves,” he says.
He explains that this is a complex topic, "because we ask them to recognize what is appropriate to spread, publish and say, and what is not, at an age when they are not yet mature."
Also, to be considerate - as far as the environment is concerned - at a time when what they want most is to be loved, to have thousands of friends and not to think about the consequences," he adds.
According to this specialist, the most effective way to show children and adolescents what privacy is, is to ask questions that make them think.
"Telling them not to do something doesn't work," he adds.
Marrielos Porras lists out some of the options: There are things you wouldn’t tell a stranger, so why do you do it on the internet?
Or: Would you like someone to post your photo the way you posted it to a friend?
Do you know what others say about you?
When you mark people in photos from celebrations, did you ask them for permission?
And one more thing: Does everyone need to know what you’re doing all the time?
The next point is to realize that they have to behave in the Internet environment as well as outside it.
They're the same rules.
“A person outside the internet is guided by respect, morality and other principles and the same should be on social networks,” he says.
Surveillance
Estuardo Guardia, a university professor, first-degree teacher and educational advisor, explains that it is essential for parents of children to carefully read the rules of social networks.
“If they understand every scam, they have a good basis for talking to children about the consequences that setting up an online account can have.
For example, as far as age is concerned or what is allowed to be shared or published," he says.
The Guardian believes it is crucial to remind children of the traditional rule of “don’t talk to strangers.”
