Starts a course that explores the "end of the world"
Every week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and bacteria, and global warming.
When Professor of Religion Stuart Charmé decided that this semester would take a course on the end of the world, he knew that it was an irresistible lure: The end of the "long number" of the Mayan calendar to come on December 21, many people caught as proof that the end of the world was coming.
Charmé, however, had no idea what awaited him in the next few months: the catastrophic Hurricane Sandy, the budget gap that some call the “debt Armageddon,” and the growing conflict Israel is drawn into, the place where Christians theorize about the end of the world will begin.
“I didn’t realize this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester ever,” Charmé told students at Rutgers University in Camden, New Jersey, this week.
When one discusses what is happening in the world today, as if we have 30 days left, it is a really good time.
And remember that evil means good for the apocalyptic minded.
And it’s not the only professor who offers courses on the “end of the world” in this semester, which is theoretically the latest in history.
At Temple University, expert assistant Barry Vacker organizes the course "The Means, Culture and the End of the World".
Every week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and bacteria, and global warming.
"We're sorting out why these ideas expand over time," he says, and how they offer hypothetical scenarios that guide certain human behavior.
For example, if nuclear material gets into the hands of terrorists, a war could break out.
This month, students analyze films with apocalyptic themes and explore how they differ from real-life examples.
"I tried to inform students about what is possible, probable, credible and impossible," says Vacker.
At the main campus of the State University of Pennsylvania, Professor of Latin American History Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solario, an expert assistant in art history and anthropology, have come together to organize a course called the simple End of the World.
"We're not joining '2012' because we're always counting on the possibility of rescheduling the course in case the world doesn't end," Restall said.
Despite "threatening destruction", students must study, create projects, and take final exams.
At Penn State, the final exam will take place on the eve of the Apocalypse, giving students no choice but to work "until the very evening of the predicted end of the world," Restall said.
Courses have become quite popular.
"It's extended to two hours," Restall said of his course for high-average students, who enrolled 35.
Weeks and weeks before the start of the semester we received an e-mail asking if there is still room.
The students themselves assure that the course is one of the most interesting.
“I find it fascinating to see what people are doing to comfort themselves,” said 23-year-old Bridgid Robinson, a student of religion and sociology from Haddonfield, New Jersey, at Rutgers University in Camden.
And so apocalyptic, secular or religious thinking is only a question of consolation or its absence.
Will Wekes, a 25-year-old student of psychology and nursing, said he had seen all the apocalyptic films.
"I've never heard of an hour when it could be taught," he said.
"I'm enjoying it."
But no professed student, let alone a professor, has said he believes in the date of the end of December 21.
“Our first project dealt with Mayan predictions and in a way we are refuting them,” said Julie Zeglen, a 21-year-old student at Temple University in West Chester.
"The Mayans never predicted the end of the world; it's just a key point on the calendar," Restall said.
But he added that in Western culture there is an apocalyptic anxiety that goes back several centuries, which people react to changes in their surroundings by forecasting the end of the world.
The rise of these speculations has been caused by the Internet.
"Otherwise people don't think about it," he said.
This happens in the vast majority of the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a professor of religion at La Salle University, who lectures in the Philippines this year, responded quickly to the question of whether he knows about a course on "the end of the world" there.
"The Philippines will not participate at the end of the world," he wrote, suggesting an exception at the top.
We have grace from the Pope.
Restall noted that many days of the Last Judgment have been spoken of over the years, saying that if nothing happens on December 21, "people will immediately start thinking about the next date" or philosophizing that December 21 is the beginning of a seven-year period at the end of which the world will disappear.
The date is taken lightly by students and professors.
Several of them said they intended to go to the "end of the world" celebrations.
"I think I'm going to call a few friends to make us laugh together," said 20-year-old communications student Samir Ford.
